Tool calls and shared files: where parallelism is safe
-------------------------------------------------------
claude9fs serializes same-path tool calls within a single tool
round: every path-carrying call (writes AND reads) is hashed by
its cleanname'd path into one of NPROC buckets, and each bucket
executes its calls sequentially in the order they were issued,
while buckets run in parallel.  Batching several edits to one
file in one round is therefore safe and applies in issue order,
and a round's process fan-out is capped at NPROC.  Successive
rounds in one session never overlap, so within a session,
same-file work is safe, period.

Caveats within a session:
- Aliases defeat the hash: the same file reached via a bind, or
  named relative in one call and absolute in another, lands in
  different buckets and is not serialized.  Use one canonical
  absolute path per file, always.
- mk is bucketed by its directory argument, not by the files
  the build reads and writes.  Don't batch an edit to a source
  file with an mk that compiles it; edit first, mk afterward
  (natural anyway -- you want the edit in place before judging
  the build).

Cross-session parallelism is NEVER coordinated -- permanently.
Serialization lives inside one session's tool round.  Two
sessions -- yours and a sub-agent's, two sub-agents on the
claudesub server, even two sessions on the same server --
execute their rounds concurrently with no shared queue, and no
code fix can add one: they are independent conversations whose
rounds the server cannot line up.  If two sessions write one
file, it is a lost-update race: both report success, the last
writer wins, and damage can include truncation.  When fanning
out sub-agents, partition file ownership so each session's
edits are disjoint, and keep shared integration files (mkfiles,
status docs) for yourself (see sub-agent-acme, "Partition file
ownership to avoid collisions").  That rule is discipline, not
a stopgap awaiting code.

Recovery if a shared file is clobbered anyway:
- Probe with identity replace_string (old == new) to learn what
  is really in the file.
- Check the tail; truncation is the characteristic damage.
- Be ready to rebuild the whole file from context with
  create_file, then re-issue dependent work.
